    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Small suckerfish with a broad, flat head, pointed ‘nose’ and double (divided) suction disc. Typically sits with the tail curled around to one side in a J-shaped posture. Common, but seldom noticed due to its small size and cryptic habits. Often found hiding inside dead mussel shells, or in similar habitats. Colour variable, but mostly pink to orange with transverse bands, especially one between eyes.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3886",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to only 5 cm.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3887",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Madeira and Canary Islands, Senegal to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to about Port Alfred.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3888",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common in rock pools and on shallow reefs to a depth of about 20 m. Usually found singly in dead bivalve shells or similar concealed habitats. Little else known about biology.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3889",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Not studied, but probably feed on smaller crustaceans and other invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3890",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Females lay eggs on the insides of dead mollusk shells. The eggs are guarded by the female until they hatch into fully-formed miniature suckerfish.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3891",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Could be confused with juvenile Rocksuckers <i>Chorisochismus dentex</i>, but attain much smaller adult size, has a double sucker, smaller teeth and a different posture, with curled-around tail.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3892",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
